 -=> Quoting Fischer1HOW SECURE is 'secring.pgtudent.msu.edu to All <=-

 Fi> I have a question :

 Fi> I realize that, when using PGP, one gives away public keys, but NEVER
 Fi> gives away the file "secring.pgp"...

 True.

 Fi> My question is this :

 Fi> IF someone gets a hold of another's "secring.pgp" file, and attempts
 Fi> to decrypt this other person's ciphertext with this stolen secret key,
 Fi> can they do it without knowing the pass phrase?

 Fi> What I am essentially asking is this : Does the pass phrase reside
 Fi> ANYWHERE within "secring.pgp", or is the file "secring.pgp" itself
 Fi> encrypted, so that even if someone steals someone elses secret key
 Fi> ring, they STILL cannot get it to work...

 It is my understanding that the passphrase is the decryption key for
 the keys on the ring. So the actual secring isn't encrypted, but the
 keys residing on secring.pgp are. I believe IDEA is used, the same
 algorithm that is used to encrypt PGP messages.

 



